# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blancmange
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Commercial almond milk comes in sweetened, unsweetened, vanilla and chocolate flavors, and is usually fortified with micronutrients as a processed food.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made at home using a blender, almonds and water.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Global almond milk sales in 2018 were US$5.8 billion, growing at 14% per year, and forecast to be a $13 billion global market by 2025.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] The earliest recipes for almond milk date back to at least the 13th century Middle East, as it was listed in Muhammad bin Hasan al-Baghdadi’s book *Kitāb al-Ṭabīḫ* (كتاب الطبيخ; *The Book of Dishes*), written in 1226.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond milk was used as a substitute for animal milk in the Middle Ages in areas that followed Catholic fasting laws.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Some recipes for almond milk have used wine in the process.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond milk's popularity as a dairy substitute continued throughout history, going well into modern times.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] It is even mentioned under the secondary definition of "milk" in Samuel Johnson's *Dictionary* in 1755, alongside pistachio milk.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In the United States, almond milk remained a niche health food item until the early 2000s, when its popularity began to increase.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In 2011 alone, almond milk sales increased by 79%.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In 2013, it surpassed soy milk as the most popular plant-based milk in the US.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] As of 2014 it comprised 60 percent of plant-milk sales and 4.1 percent of total milk sales in the US.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Manufacturers and distributors of animal milk have advocated that plant-based milk not be labelled as "milk".
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] They complain that consumers may be confused between the two, and that plant-based milks are not necessarily as nutritious in terms of vitamins and minerals.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In the case of the United States, the FDA said in 2023 that plant-based milk could be labeled as milk, but that producers should note the nutritional differences from regular milk.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] European Union regulations require "milk" to be used for animals only, except coconut milk.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Within the Italian regions of Sicily, Apulia, Calabria, and Campania, almond milk is a protected traditional agricultural product.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Vitamin A fortification is only required for skimmed milk in the US.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Vitamin D fortification for milk is mandatory in the US.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] If unfortified, almond milk has less vitamin D than fortified cow milk; in North America, cow milk must be fortified with vitamin D, but vitamins are added to plant milks on a voluntary basis.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Vitamin E is released from the almonds and absorbed.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] The positive effects of the vitamin E include strengthening the cells.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Because of its low protein content (0.4 g per 100 ml), almond milk is not a suitable replacement for breast milk, cow milk, or hydrolyzed formulas for children under two years of age.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] The general production method involves soaking and grinding almonds in an excess of water.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] A milky white liquid is obtained after filtering the almond pulp (flesh).
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond milk can also be made by adding water to almond butter.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In commercial production, almond milk is homogenised with high pressure and pasteurised for greater stability and shelf life.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond milk can be stored in the fridge in an air-tight container (preferably a glass container) for about 4–5 days.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] However, certain factors, such as the temperature of the refrigerator, sterilization of the blender or storing jar, and surface cleanliness, can decide how many days you can keep it fresh.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Storing homemade almond milk for more than a week may reduce its nutrition or even make it unhealthy.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In July 2015, a class action lawsuit was filed in New York City against two American manufacturers, Blue Diamond Growers and White Wave Foods, for false advertising regarding the small quantity of almonds (only 2%) contained in the final product.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In October 2015, a judge denied the plaintiff's request for an injunction.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, and abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Due to the persistent droughts in California in the early 21st century, it became more difficult to raise almonds in a sustainable manner.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Almond sustainability is challenged because of the high amount of water needed to grow almonds: a single glass of almond milk requires roughly 74 litres (16 imp gal; 20 US gal) of water to produce.
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Among plant-based milks, almond milk requires substantially more water during the growing and production stages than soy, rice or oat milk (graph).
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] Dairy milk requires more water to produce than almond milk (graph).
[src:blancmange/almond-milk] In 2014, California produced 42.3 billion pounds of cow's milk and only 2.14 billion pounds of almond milk.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] The name "tofu" here refers to "tofu-like solid"; soy beans, which are the main ingredient of tofu, are not used, nor coagulated as soybeans would be to make tofu.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] This naming convention is also seen in other East Asian dishes, such as Chinese *yúdòufu* (魚豆腐) and Japanese *gomadōfu* (胡麻豆腐).
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] Apricot kernel milk is often confused with almond milk, as apricot kernel itself is often confused with almond.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] In the traditional recipe, the primary flavoring agent is apricot kernels, soaked and ground with water.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] The mixture is strained, sweetened, and heated with a gelling agent (usually agar).
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] When chilled, the apricot kernel milk mixture solidifies into the consistency of a soft gelatin dessert.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] Although the agar-based recipe is vegan, there are numerous nontraditional recipes that are not.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] Most are based on dairy products and a small amount of flavored extract.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] Gelatin is also a common substitute for agar.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] Annin jelly can be made from scratch or using instant mix.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] There is an instant soy-based powder with a coagulating agent, which dissolves in hot water and solidifies upon cooling.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] In Taiwanese cuisine, the dish uses the sweeter southern variety of apricot kernels which are mixed with peanuts.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] In Taipei, the dessert originated as a food stall dish, but is now also served in banquets halls and hotel restaurants.
[src:blancmange/almond-tofu] In Hawaii where it is commonly known as "almond float," it was introduced by Chinese immigrants starting in the 1850s, it is now usually made with gelatin and almond extract and typically mixed with canned fruit cocktail and canned lychee.
[src:blancmange/almond] ***Prunus dulcis*** (Mill.) D.A.Webb, nom. illeg. non *Prunus dulcis* Rouchy) is a species of tree from the genus *Prunus*.
[src:blancmange/almond] Along with the peach, it is classified in the subgenus *Amygdalus*, distinguished from the other subgenera by corrugations on the woody shell (endocarp) surrounding the seed.
[src:blancmange/almond] The fruit of the almond is a drupe, consisting of an outer hull and a hard shell with the seed, which is not a true nut.
[src:blancmange/almond] *Shelling* almonds refers to removing the shell to reveal the seed.
[src:blancmange/almond] Blanched almonds are unshelled almonds that have been treated with hot water to soften the outer skin, which is then removed to reveal the white embryo.
[src:blancmange/almond] Once almonds are cleaned and processed, they can be stored for around a year if kept refrigerated; at higher temperatures they will become rancid more quickly.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are used in many cuisines, often featuring prominently in desserts, such as marzipan.
[src:blancmange/almond] The almond tree prospers in a moderate Mediterranean climate with cool winter weather.
[src:blancmange/almond] It is rarely found wild in its original setting.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees, due to the ability to produce quality offspring entirely from seed, without using suckers and cuttings.
[src:blancmange/almond] Evidence of domesticated almonds in the Early Bronze Age has been found in the archeological sites of the Middle East, and subsequently across the Mediterranean region and similar arid climates with cool winters.
[src:blancmange/almond] California produces about 80% of the world's almond supply.
[src:blancmange/almond] Due to high acreage and water demand for almond cultivation, and need for pesticides, California almond production may be unsustainable, especially during the persistent drought and heat from climate change in the 21st century.
[src:blancmange/almond] Droughts in California have caused some producers to leave the industry, leading to lower supply and increased prices.
[src:blancmange/almond] The almond is a deciduous tree growing to 3–4.5 metres (10–15 feet) in height, with a trunk of up to 30 centimetres (12 inches) in diameter.
[src:blancmange/almond] The young twigs are green at first, becoming purplish where exposed to sunlight, then grey in their second year.
[src:blancmange/almond] The leaves are 8–13 cm (3–5 in) long, with a serrated margin and a 2.5 cm (1 in) petiole.
[src:blancmange/almond] The fragrant flowers are white to pale pink, 3–5 cm (1–2 in) diameter with five petals, produced singly or in pairs and appearing before the leaves in early spring.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond trees thrive in Mediterranean climates with warm, dry summers and mild, wet winters.
[src:blancmange/almond] The optimal temperature for their growth is between 15 and 30 °C (59 and 86 °F) and the tree buds have a chilling requirement of 200 to 700 hours below 7.2 °C (45.0 °F) to break dormancy.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds begin bearing an economic crop in the third year after planting.
[src:blancmange/almond] Trees reach full bearing five to six years after planting.
[src:blancmange/almond] The fruit matures in the autumn, 7–8 months after flowering.
[src:blancmange/almond] The outer covering, consisting of an outer exocarp, or skin, and mesocarp, or flesh, fleshy in other members of *Prunus* such as the plum and cherry, is instead a thick, leathery, grey-green coat (with a downy exterior), called the hull.
[src:blancmange/almond] Inside the hull is a woody endocarp which forms a reticulated, hard shell (like the outside of a peach pit) called the pyrena.
[src:blancmange/almond] Inside the shell is the edible seed, commonly called a nut.
[src:blancmange/almond] Generally, one seed is present, but occasionally two occur.
[src:blancmange/almond] After the fruit matures, the hull splits and separates from the shell, and an abscission layer forms between the stem and the fruit so that the fruit can fall from the tree.
[src:blancmange/almond] During harvest, mechanised tree shakers are used to expedite fruits falling to the ground for collection.
[src:blancmange/almond] The almond was named *Amygdalus communis* by Carl Linnaeus in his Species plantarum in 1753.
[src:blancmange/almond] For the name 'Amygdalus' he referred to Gaspard Bauhin's *Pinax* (1623).
[src:blancmange/almond] In 1801 the species was for the first time placed in the genus *Prunus* by August Batsch.
[src:blancmange/almond] In that genus, the name *Prunus communis* was no longer available because in 1778 William Hudson had already assigned it to a taxon in which he included the plum (*Prunus domestica*).
[src:blancmange/almond] Batsch thereupon named the species *Prunus amygdalus*, where 'amygdalus' is the old generic name and should therefore be treated as a noun in apposition.
[src:blancmange/almond] Meanwhile, in 1768, Philip Miller had published the name of what he believed to be a second species of almond: *Amygdalus dulcis*.
[src:blancmange/almond] He mentioned Linnaeus' *Amygdalus communis* as the first species.
[src:blancmange/almond] It was not until 1967 that the combination *Prunus dulcis* was published for the almond by David Allardice Webb, on the assumption that *Amygdalus dulcis* was nothing more than a synonym of *Amygdalus communis*, and thus an available name for that species.
[src:blancmange/almond] The epithet *dulcis* (1768) is older than *amygdalus* (1801) and would therefore have priority.
[src:blancmange/almond] Webb noted that it was unfortunate that a species known for 165 years as *Prunus amygdalus* now had to be renamed under the rules of nomenclature.
[src:blancmange/almond] However, it later turned out that in 1967 the name *Prunus dulcis* was no longer available for the almond because it had already been used for a cherry in an 1878 publication by L'Abbé Rouchy.
[src:blancmange/almond] The oldest valid combination in *Prunus* is therefore *Prunus amygdalus*.
[src:blancmange/almond] *dulcis* are predominantly sweet but some individual trees produce seeds that are somewhat more bitter.
[src:blancmange/almond] The genetic basis for bitterness involves a single gene, the bitter flavour furthermore being recessive, both aspects making this trait easier to domesticate.
[src:blancmange/almond] *amara* are always bitter, as are the kernels from other species of genus *Prunus*, such as apricot, peach and cherry (although to a lesser extent).
[src:blancmange/almond] The bitter almond is slightly broader and shorter than the sweet almond and contains about 50% of the fixed oil that occurs in sweet almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] It contains the enzyme emulsin which, in the presence of water, acts on the two soluble glucosides amygdalin and prunasin yielding glucose, cyanide and the essential oil of bitter almonds, which is nearly pure benzaldehyde, the chemical causing the bitter flavour.
[src:blancmange/almond] Bitter almonds may yield 4–9 milligrams of hydrogen cyanide per almond and contain 42 times higher amounts of cyanide than the trace levels found in sweet almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] The origin of cyanide content in bitter almonds is via the enzymatic hydrolysis of amygdalin.
[src:blancmange/almond] P450 monooxygenases are involved in the amygdalin biosynthetic pathway.
[src:blancmange/almond] A point mutation in a bHLH transcription factor prevents transcription of the two cytochrome P450 genes, resulting in the sweet kernel trait.
[src:blancmange/almond] The word *almond* is a loanword from Old French *almande* or *alemande*, descended from Late Latin *amandula*, *amindula*, modified from Classical Latin *amygdala*, which is in turn borrowed from Ancient Greek *amygdálē* (ἀμυγδάλη) (cf. amygdala, an almond-shaped portion of the brain).
[src:blancmange/almond] Late Old English had *amygdales* 'almonds'.
[src:blancmange/almond] The adjective *amygdaloid* (literally 'like an almond, almond-like') is used to describe objects which are roughly almond-shaped, particularly a shape which is part way between a triangle and an ellipse.
[src:blancmange/almond] For example, the amygdala of the brain uses a direct borrowing of the Greek term *amygdalē*.
[src:blancmange/almond] The precise origin of the almond is controversial due to estimates for its emergence across wide geographic regions.
[src:blancmange/almond] Sources indicate that its origins were in an area stretching across Central Asia, Iran, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Kurdistan, Afghanistan, and Iraq, or in an eastern Asian subregion between Mongolia and Uzbekistan.
[src:blancmange/almond] In other assessments, both botanical and archaeological evidence indicates that almonds originated and were first cultivated in West Asia, particularly in countries of the Levant.
[src:blancmange/almond] Most recent sources specified Iran and Anatolia (present day Turkey) as origin locations of the almond, with Iran as the main origin centre.
[src:blancmange/almond] The wild form of domesticated almond grew in parts of the Levant.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond cultivation was spread by humans centuries ago along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea into northern Africa and southern Europe, and more recently to other world regions, notably California.
[src:blancmange/almond] Selection of the sweet type from the many bitter types in the wild marked the beginning of almond domestication.
[src:blancmange/almond] The wild ancestor of the almond used to breed the domesticated species is unknown.
[src:blancmange/almond] The species *Prunus fenzliana* may be the most likely wild ancestor of the almond, in part because it is native to Armenia and western Azerbaijan, where it was apparently domesticated.
[src:blancmange/almond] Wild almond species were grown by early farmers, "at first unintentionally in the garbage heaps, and later intentionally in their orchards".
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds were one of the earliest domesticated fruit trees owing to their ability to be grown from seed, allowing their cultivation to have perhaps predated the advent of grafting.
[src:blancmange/almond] Domesticated almonds appear in the Early Bronze Age (3000–2000 BCE), such as the archaeological sites of Numeira (Jordan), or possibly earlier.
[src:blancmange/almond] They were found in Tutankhamun's tomb in Egypt (c.
[src:blancmange/almond] 1325 BCE), probably imported from the Levant.
[src:blancmange/almond] Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century *Book on Agriculture* includes an article on almond tree cultivation in Spain.
[src:blancmange/almond] Of the European countries that the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh reported as cultivating almonds, Germany is the northernmost, though the domesticated form can be found as far north as Iceland.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond trees are small to medium-sized but commercial cultivars can be grafted onto a different root-stock to produce smaller trees.
[src:blancmange/almond] Breeding programs have found a high shell-seal trait, which reduces insect damage and mold contamination.
[src:blancmange/almond] The most widely planted varieties of almond are self-incompatible; hence these trees require pollen from a tree with different genetic characters to produce seeds.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond orchards therefore must grow mixtures of almond varieties.
[src:blancmange/almond] In addition, the pollen is transferred from flower to flower by insects; therefore commercial growers must ensure there are enough insects to perform this task.
[src:blancmange/almond] The large scale of almond production in the U.S. creates a significant problem of providing enough pollinating insects.
[src:blancmange/almond] Additional pollinating insects are therefore brought to the trees.
[src:blancmange/almond] The pollination of California's almonds is the largest annual managed pollination event in the world, with over 1 million hives (nearly half of all beehives in the U.S.) being brought to the almond orchards each February.
[src:blancmange/almond] Much of the supply of bees is managed by pollination brokers, who contract with migratory beekeepers from at least 49 states for the event.
[src:blancmange/almond] This business was heavily affected by colony collapse disorder at the turn of the 21st century, causing a nationwide shortage of honey bees and increasing the price of insect pollination.
[src:blancmange/almond] To partially protect almond growers from these costs, researchers at the Agricultural Research Service, part of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), developed self-pollinating almond trees that combine this character with quality characters such as a flavour and yield.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond trees can be attacked by an array of damaging microbes, fungal pathogens, plant viruses, and bacteria.
[src:blancmange/almond] Pavement ants (*Tetramorium caespitum*), southern fire ants (*Solenopsis xyloni*), and thief ants (*Solenopsis molesta*) are seed predators.
[src:blancmange/almond] *Bryobia rubrioculus* mites are most known for their damage to this crop.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond production in California is concentrated mainly in the Central Valley, where the mild climate, rich soil, abundant sunshine and water supply make for ideal growing conditions.
[src:blancmange/almond] The issue is complex because of the high amount of water needed to produce almonds: a single almond requires roughly 1.1 US gallons (0.92 imperial gallons; 4.2 litres) of water to grow properly.
[src:blancmange/almond] Regulations related to water supplies are changing so some growers have destroyed their current almond orchards to replace with either younger trees or a different crop such as pistachio that needs less water.
[src:blancmange/almond] California almond farmers have promoted growing use of sustainable farming practices, including introduction of water-efficient irrigation technology, funding of honeybee health research, and productively using waste biomass (such as shells) in pursuit of a zero waste industry.
[src:blancmange/almond] In 2023, world production of almonds was 3.5 million tonnes, led by the United States with 51% of the total, followed by Spain and Australia as secondary producers (table).
[src:blancmange/almond] Australia is the largest almond production region in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:blancmange/almond] Most of the country's almond orchards are located along the Murray River corridor in New South Wales, Victoria, or South Australia.
[src:blancmange/almond] In the Australian financial year 1 July 2024–30 June 2025, the national almond crop fell 5%, but increased in value by 20%, to a record A$1.3 billion.
[src:blancmange/almond] India was the second-largest export market, at 19,803 t (19,490 long tons; 21,829 short tons), a tonnage similar to that of the previous financial year.
[src:blancmange/almond] As of late February 2026, Australia was forecast to harvest a record almond crop of 167,000 t (164,000 long tons; 184,000 short tons) in the 2025–26 financial year.
[src:blancmange/almond] Spain has diverse commercial cultivars of almonds grown in Catalonia, Valencia, Murcia, Andalusia, and Aragón regions, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:blancmange/almond] The almond cultivar 'Marcona' is unique, having a kernel that is short, round, relatively sweet, and delicate in texture; it is marketed by name.
[src:blancmange/almond] Its origin is unknown, but has been grown in Spain over centuries.
[src:blancmange/almond] In the U.S., production is concentrated in California where 400,000 ha (1,000,000 acres) and six different almond varieties were under cultivation in 2017, with a yield of 2.25 billion pounds (1.02 billion kilograms) of shelled almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] California production is marked by a period of intense pollination during late winter by rented commercial bees transported by truck across the U.S. to almond groves, requiring more than half of the total U.S. commercial honeybee population.
[src:blancmange/almond] The value of total U.S. exports of shelled almonds in 2016 was $3.2 billion.
[src:blancmange/almond] All commercially grown almonds sold as food in the U.S. are sweet cultivars.
[src:blancmange/almond] Food and Drug Administration reported in 2010 that some fractions of imported sweet almonds were contaminated with bitter almonds, which contain cyanide.
[src:blancmange/almond] Bitter almonds contain some 40 times the trace levels of cyanide found in sweet almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] Extract of bitter almond was once used medicinally, but even in small doses, its effects are severe or lethal, especially in children; the cyanide must be removed before consumption.
[src:blancmange/almond] The acute oral lethal dose of cyanide for adult humans is reported to be 0.5–3.5 mg/kg (0.2–1.6 mg/lb) of body weight (approximately 50 bitter almonds for the average adult), so that for children consuming 5–10 bitter almonds may be fatal.
[src:blancmange/almond] Symptoms of eating such almonds include vertigo and other typical cyanide poisoning effects.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds may cause allergy or intolerance.
[src:blancmange/almond] Cross-reactivity is common with peach allergens (lipid transfer proteins) and tree nut allergens.
[src:blancmange/almond] Symptoms range from local signs and symptoms (e.g., oral allergy syndrome, contact urticaria) to systemic signs and symptoms including anaphylaxis (e.g., urticaria, angioedema, gastrointestinal and respiratory symptoms).
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are susceptible to aflatoxin-producing moulds.
[src:blancmange/almond] Aflatoxins are potent carcinogenic chemicals produced by moulds such as *Aspergillus flavus* and *Aspergillus parasiticus*.
[src:blancmange/almond] The mould contamination may occur from soil, previously infested almonds, and almond pests such as navel-orange worm.
[src:blancmange/almond] High levels of mould growth typically appear as grey to black filament-like growth.
[src:blancmange/almond] It is unsafe to eat mould-infected tree nuts.
[src:blancmange/almond] Some countries have strict limits on allowable levels of aflatoxin contamination of almonds and require adequate testing before the nuts can be marketed to their citizens.
[src:blancmange/almond] The European Union, for example, introduced a requirement since 2007 that all almond shipments to the EU be tested for aflatoxin.
[src:blancmange/almond] If aflatoxin does not meet the strict safety regulations, either the entire consignment must be reprocessed to eliminate the aflatoxin or it must be destroyed.
[src:blancmange/almond] After tracing cases of salmonellosis to almonds, the USDA approved a proposal by the Almond Board of California to pasteurize almonds sold to the public.
[src:blancmange/almond] After publishing the rule in March 2007, the almond pasteurization program became mandatory for California companies effective 1 September 2007.
[src:blancmange/almond] Raw, untreated California almonds have not been commercially available in the U.S. since then.
[src:blancmange/almond] California almonds labelled "raw" must be steam-pasteurized or chemically treated with propylene oxide (PPO).
[src:blancmange/almond] This does not apply to imported almonds or almonds sold from the grower directly to the consumer in small quantities.
[src:blancmange/almond] The Almond Board of California states: "PPO residue dissipates after treatment".
[src:blancmange/almond] Environmental Protection Agency has reported: "Propylene oxide has been detected in fumigated food products; consumption of contaminated food is another possible route of exposure".
[src:blancmange/almond] PPO is classified as Group 2B ("possibly carcinogenic to humans").
[src:blancmange/almond] The USDA-approved marketing order was challenged in court by organic farmers organized by the Cornucopia Institute, a Wisconsin-based farm policy research group which filed a lawsuit in September 2008.
[src:blancmange/almond] According to the institute, this almond marketing order has imposed significant financial burdens on small-scale and organic growers and damaged domestic almond markets.
[src:blancmange/almond] A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit in early 2009 on procedural grounds.
[src:blancmange/almond] In August 2010, a federal appeals court ruled that the farmers have a right to appeal the USDA regulation.
[src:blancmange/almond] In March 2013, the court vacated the suit on the basis that the objections should have been raised in 2007 when the regulation was first proposed.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are 4% water, 22% carbohydrates, 21% protein, and 50% fat (table).
[src:blancmange/almond] Per 100 g, almonds contain dietary fiber (12 g), the monounsaturated fat, oleic acid (31 g), and the polyunsaturated fat, linoleic acid (12 g; table source).
[src:blancmange/almond] Typical of nuts and seeds, almonds are a source of phytosterols, such as beta-sitosterol.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are included as a good source of protein among recommended healthy foods by the USDA.
[src:blancmange/almond] A 2016 review of clinical research indicated that regular consumption of almonds may reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering blood levels of LDL cholesterol.
[src:blancmange/almond] While the almond is often eaten on its own, raw or toasted, it is also a component of various dishes.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are available in many forms, such as whole, slivered, and ground into flour.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond pieces around 2–3 millimetres (1⁄16–1⁄8 in) in size, called "nibs", are used for special purposes such as decoration.
[src:blancmange/almond] A wide range of classic sweets feature almonds as a central ingredient.
[src:blancmange/almond] Marzipan was developed in the Middle Ages.
[src:blancmange/almond] Since the 19th century almonds have been used to make bread, almond butter, cakes and puddings, candied confections, almond cream-filled pastries, nougat, cookies (macaroons, biscotti and qurabiya), and cakes (financiers, Esterházy torte), and other sweets and desserts.
[src:blancmange/almond] In Saudi Arabia, almonds are a typical embellishment for the rice dish kabsa.
[src:blancmange/almond] Spanish cookery uses almonds in sweet dishes as well as in savory ones, ground up to thicken sauces and stews.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds can be processed into a milk substitute called almond milk; the nut's soft texture, mild flavour, and light colouring (when skinned) make for an efficient analog to dairy, and a soy-free choice for lactose intolerant people and vegans.
[src:blancmange/almond] Raw, blanched, and lightly toasted almonds work well for different production techniques, some of which are similar to that of soy milk and some of which use no heat, resulting in raw milk.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond milk, along with almond butter and almond oil, are versatile products used in both sweet and savoury dishes.
[src:blancmange/almond] In Moroccan cuisine, sharbat billooz, a common beverage, is made by blending blanched almonds with milk, sugar and other flavourings.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almond flour or ground almond meal combined with sugar or honey as marzipan is often used as a gluten-free alternative to wheat flour in cooking and baking.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds contain polyphenols in their skins consisting of flavonols, flavan-3-ols, hydroxybenzoic acids and flavanones analogous to those of certain fruits and vegetables.
[src:blancmange/almond] These phenolic compounds and almond skin prebiotic dietary fibre have commercial interest as food additives or dietary supplements.
[src:blancmange/almond] Historically, almond syrup was an emulsion of sweet and bitter almonds, usually made with barley syrup (orgeat syrup) or in a syrup of orange flower water and sugar, often flavoured with a synthetic aroma of almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] Orgeat syrup is an important ingredient in the Mai Tai and many other Tiki drinks.
[src:blancmange/almond] Due to the cyanide found in bitter almonds, modern syrups generally are produced only from sweet almonds.
[src:blancmange/almond] Such syrup products do not contain significant levels of hydrocyanic acid, so are generally considered safe for human consumption.
[src:blancmange/almond] Almonds are a rich source of oil, with 50% of kernel dry mass as fat (whole almond nutrition table).
[src:blancmange/almond] In relation to total dry mass of the kernel, almond oil contains 32% monounsaturated oleic acid (an omega-9 fatty acid), 13% linoleic acid (a polyunsaturated omega-6 essential fatty acid), and 10% saturated fatty acid (mainly as palmitic acid).
[src:blancmange/almond] Linolenic acid, a polyunsaturated omega-3 fat, is not present (table).
[src:blancmange/almond] When almond oil is analyzed separately and expressed per 100 grams as a reference mass, the oil provides 3,700 kJ (884 kcal) of food energy, 8 grams of saturated fat (81% of which is palmitic acid), 70 grams of oleic acid, and 17 grams of linoleic acid (oil table).
[src:blancmange/almond] The almond is highly revered in some cultures.
[src:blancmange/almond] In the Bible, the almond is mentioned ten times, beginning with Genesis 43:11, where it is described as "among the best of fruits".
[src:blancmange/almond] In Numbers 17, Levi is chosen from the other tribes of Israel by Aaron's rod, which brought forth almond flowers.
[src:blancmange/almond] In Jeremiah 1:11–12, the vision of an almond branch conveys a wordplay in Hebrew between *shaqed* (almond) and *shoqed* (watching), symbolizing God's vigilant commitment to fulfill His word.
[src:blancmange/almond] Many Sephardic Jews give five almonds to each guest before special occasions like weddings.
[src:blancmange/almond] Similarly, Christian symbolism often uses almond branches as a symbol of the virgin birth of Jesus; paintings and icons often include almond-shaped haloes encircling the Christ Child and as a symbol of Mary.
[src:blancmange/almond] The word "luz", which appears in Genesis 30:37, sometimes translated as "hazel", may actually be derived from the Aramaic name for almond (Luz), and is translated as such in the New International Version and other versions of the Bible.
[src:blancmange/almond] The Entrance of the flower (*La entrada de la flor*) is an event celebrated on 1 February in Torrent, Spain, in which the clavarios and members of the Confrerie of the Mother of God deliver a branch of the first-blooming almond-tree to the Virgin.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Archaeological studies in the Americas show evidence of arrowroot cultivation as early as 7,000 years ago.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The name may come from *aru-aru* (meal of meals) in the language of the Caribbean Arawak people, for whom the plant was a staple.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It has also been suggested that the name comes from arrowroot's use in treating poison-arrow wounds, as it draws out the poison when applied to the site of the injury.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] In the early days of carbonless copy paper, arrowroot starch, because of its appropriate grain-size, was a widely used ingredient.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] After an economical way of centrifugally separating wheat flour was devised, arrowroot lost its role in papermaking.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Saint Vincent has a long history of arrowroot production.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The industry started as the food and medicine of the Carib and Garifuna peoples and developed to the status of a major export of St.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It became an important commodity in colonial trade in the 1930s.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] As the sugar industry declined in the nineteenth century, cultivation of arrowroot was developed to fill the void.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Since then, the area cultivated has declined steadily as other crops, particularly bananas, have gained wider acceptance by farmers.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Evidence of its former importance is indicated by the ruins of the various magnificent 19th-century factories located in valleys on the St.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot cultivation is now concentrated on farms located north of the Rabacca River, particularly in the Owia area.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] This is also the area where the population of Carib descent is concentrated.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Vincent arrowroot industry played an important role in the economy of the island, contributing close to 50% of the country's foreign export earnings, and was the principal source of employment and income of the rural people from the 1930s to the 1960s.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The plant is propagated from rhizomes and cultivation takes place at elevations up to 300 metres on the eastern and windward facing side of the highlands of St.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Cultivation covers an area of about 3,700 ha and some 80% of the crop is grown by small farmers.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The arrowroot plant is very hardy and not very demanding in its requirements.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Vincent, particularly the north-east coast, provides the ideal growing conditions for optimal yields: deep, well drained, slightly acidic soils and a hot, humid climate.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Some farmers produce the crop by shifting cultivation on the cleared forested slopes.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The harvesting season extends from October to May.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] On the larger estates, the harvesting of the rhizome usually proceeds from the base of a hill towards the top.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Harvesting involves breaking off the rhizome from the shoot.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Planting and harvesting are inter-related in that when the rhizomes are harvested the shoot is replanted at the same time.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Vincent, much use is made of rural unemployment, and many women workers are involved in the various phases of operation.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Mechanical harvesters have recently been introduced, allowing faster arrowroot harvesting.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Six factories process the island's arrowroot and large processing plants are located at Belle Vue and at Owia.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot tubers contain about 23% starch.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] They are first washed and then cleaned of the paper-like scale.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The scales must be carefully removed before extracting the starch because they impart a disagreeable flavour.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] After removing the scale, the roots are washed again, drained and finally reduced to a pulp by beating them in mortars or subjecting them to the action of a wheel rasp.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The milky liquid thus obtained is passed through a coarse cloth or hair sieve and the pure starch, which is insoluble, is allowed to settle at the bottom.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The wet starch is dried in the sun or in a drying house.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The result is a powder, the "arrowroot" of commerce, that is quickly packed for market in air-tight cans, packages or cases.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot starch has in the past been quite extensively adulterated with potato starch and other similar substances.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Microscopically the arrow root starch is oval in shape and with hilum at the proximal end.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot can be consumed in the form of biscuits, such as Arnott's milk arrowroot biscuits.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It may also be used as an ingredient in puddings, jellies, cakes, hot sauces, and also with beef tea, milk or veal broth.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Kudzu arrowroot (*Pueraria lobata*) is used in noodles in Korean and Vietnamese cuisine.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] In the Victorian era it was used, boiled with a little flavouring added, as an easily digestible food for children and people with dietary restrictions.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot makes clear, shimmering fruit gels and prevents ice crystals from forming in homemade ice cream.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It can also be used as a thickener for acidic foods, such as East Asian sweet and sour sauce.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It is used in cooking to produce a clear, thickened sauce, such as a fruit sauce.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It will not make the sauce go cloudy, like cornstarch, flour, or other starchy thickening agents would do.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The lack of gluten in arrowroot flour makes it useful as a replacement for wheat flour for those with a gluten intolerance.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It is, however, relatively high in carbohydrates and low in protein (approximately 7.7%) and does not provide a complete substitute for wheat flour in bread-making.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] In Filipino cuisine, Arrowroot flour is used to make uraro or arrowroot cookies.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Arrowroot thickens at a lower temperature than flour or cornstarch, is not weakened by acidic ingredients, has a more neutral taste, and is not affected by freezing.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It does not mix well with dairy, forming a slimy mixture.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] It is recommended that arrowroot be mixed with a cool liquid before adding to a hot fluid.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] The mixture should be heated only until the mixture thickens and removed immediately to prevent the mixture from thinning.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Overheating tends to break down arrowroot's thickening property.
[src:blancmange/arrowroot] Two teaspoons of arrowroot can be substituted for one tablespoon of cornstarch, or one teaspoon of arrowroot for one tablespoon of wheat flour.
[src:blancmange/ashure] In the Balkans and Turkey, Muslims make the dish during the month of Muharram in which the Day of Ashura takes place.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Armenians make it as a Christmas pudding and for New Year's celebrations, where it is a centerpiece, Sephardic Jews prepare the dish to celebrate the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:blancmange/ashure] In some Jewish, Christian, and Muslim traditions, a similar dish is prepared to commemorate a child's first tooth, or the passing of a family member.
[src:blancmange/ashure] For the people of the ancient Near East, foods composed of boiled whole grains came to be associated with spring and harvest rites since ancient times.
[src:blancmange/ashure] This association spread to Asia, Europe, and Africa.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Rites related with Tammuz, the Babylonian god of wheat and fertility, were recorded as late as the 10th century by an Arab traveler who wrote about boiled wheat among the dishes consumed at a pagan celebration held at Harran.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Jews, Christians and Muslims have all consumed boiled wheat in a variety of ways under various names for millennia.
[src:blancmange/ashure] These dishes have been sweetened in various ways with sugar, fruit molasses, and dried fruits.
[src:blancmange/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Ararat, the family of Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding and that "pudding" is now called *anoushabour*.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Armenians make anoushabur to commemorate this event, but also other events.
[src:blancmange/ashure] After a baby is born, Armenian families observe a period of seclusion for up to 40 days, culminating in a baptism ceremony (knunk).
[src:blancmange/ashure] In general, Armenians enjoy anoushabur as a part of festive spreads.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Armenian sources note it was cleverly used to maintain the fast, yet celebrate Christmas eve with a sweet treat.
[src:blancmange/ashure] It’s also used in thanksgiving offerings, during weddings or house blessings.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Sharing Anoushabur is a gesture of communal warmth, linking family, faith, and gratitude.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Anoushabur is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Since Armenians serve this pudding during Christmas (6 January) and on New Year's Eve (Armenians of Jerusalem celebrate it at 13 January), it is sometimes called "Armenian Christmas Pudding".
[src:blancmange/ashure] This traditional Armenian sweet porridge is made from wheat or barley, dried fruits (such as apricots, raisins, and prunes), sugar, spices (like vanilla and cinnamon) and nuts (almonds and pistachios are most common).
[src:blancmange/ashure] The grains are simmered until tender, then combined with the fruits and nuts, then sweetened, and flavored with rose water and the spices.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Anoushabur may be garnished with pomegranate seeds, dried fruits and cinnamon.
[src:blancmange/ashure] The pudding may be accompanied by multiple Armenian desserts and nuts, such as almonds or pistachios.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Anoushabur (անուշապուր) is a compound Armenian word.
[src:blancmange/ashure] "Anoush" (անուշ) means sweet and "Abur" (ապուր) means soup or porridge, so the word Anoushabur literally means "Sweet soup" or "Sweet porridge".
[src:blancmange/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Cudi or Mount Ararat, the family of Nuh or Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding, what is now called *ashure*.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Turkish families make ashure pudding to commemorate this event.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Ashure is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:blancmange/ashure] According to a late Ottoman writer, passages from the Quran were spoken over the cauldron of cooked aşure in memory of deceased family members before it was served to neighbors, suggesting that for certain Sunni families the meal had a connection to remembering the deceased.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Today, a dish akin to this is prepared to honor a child's first tooth.
[src:blancmange/ashure] According to the Ottoman historian Ahmed Cavid (d.
[src:blancmange/ashure] 1803), women gave it away to loved ones, friends, and the impoverished as a gesture of gratitude for the child's survival of the difficult first year of life.
[src:blancmange/ashure] In Turkey and many other Middle Eastern countries, this tradition is still common among Christians, Jews, and Muslims.
[src:blancmange/ashure] The dish can be either sweet or savory and is known in Turkey as diş buğday ('tooth wheat').
[src:blancmange/ashure] Aşure is also made during the Hıdırellez spring celebration, which is the occasion where it is most similar to its ancient pagan roots.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Sephardic Jews prepare Ashure, also known as "*trigo koço*", for the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:blancmange/ashure] It is made out of boiling wheat grains combined with sugar, crushed walnuts, and cinnamon.
[src:blancmange/ashure] According to Aylin Öney Tan, this practice may have originated from early Jewish communities in Anatolia during the Byzantine period rather than being brought to Ottoman Turkey by Sephardic Jews who settled there following their expulsion from Spain and Portugal in the late 15th century.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Several Jewish communities prepare Ashura, also known as *b'Lila*, to celebrate a child's first tooth.
[src:blancmange/ashure] This dish is prepared in Bosnia and Bulgaria under the names hašure and ashoure, respectively.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Ashure porridge does not have a single recipe, as recipes vary between regions and families.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Traditionally, it is said to have at least seven ingredients.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Some say at least ten ingredients must be used, in keeping with the theme of "tenth", while Alevis always use twelve.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Among these are wheat, barley, rice, white beans, chickpeas, pekmez, date molasses, pomegranate molasses, beet juice, dried fruits like dates, raisins, currants, apricots, figs, apples and nuts like pistachios, almonds, hazelnuts, walnuts, pine nuts and sesame seeds.
[src:blancmange/ashure] However, many renditions add orange, lemon and lime peel to add depth to the pudding.
[src:blancmange/ashure] Anise seed, black cumin seeds, prunus mahaleb, pomegranate arils, cardamom, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, allspice and desiccated or shredded coconut may be used as garnish, and some variations are flavored with anise liqueur, rose water and/or orange blossom water.
[src:blancmange/ashure] The word Ashure comes from the Arabic word "Ashura" (Arabic: عَاشُوْرَاء **ʿĀshūrāʾ**), meaning 'tenth'.
[src:blancmange/asida] Asida is particularly common in Sudan, Morocco, Libya, Algeria, Tunisia, Yemen, Ethiopia, Eritrea, and the rest of the Middle East.
[src:blancmange/asida] Often served during religious holidays such as Mawlid and Eid, it is also served during other traditional ceremonies—for example, those accompanying the birth of a child, such as the *‘aqīqah*, the cutting of the hair of a newborn seven days after birth.
[src:blancmange/asida] A simple, yet rich dish, often eaten without other complementary dishes, it is traditionally served at breakfast and is also given to women in labor.
[src:blancmange/asida] The name *asida* is derived from the Arabic root عصد (ʿ-ṣ-d), associated with twisting or kneading.
[src:blancmange/asida] One of the earliest documented recipes for asida is found in a tenth century Arabic cookbook by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq called *Kitab al-Ṭabīḫ* (Arabic: كتاب الطبيخ, *The Book of Dishes*).
[src:blancmange/asida] It was described as a thick pudding of dates cooked with clarified butter (*samn*).
[src:blancmange/asida] A recipe for asida was also mentioned in an anonymous Hispano-Muslim cookbook dating to the 13th century.
[src:blancmange/asida] In the 13th and 14th centuries, in the mountainous region of the Rif along the Mediterranean coast of Morocco, a flour made from lightly grilled barley was used in place of wheat flour.
[src:blancmange/asida] A recipe for asida that adds argan seed oil was documented by Leo Africanus (c.
[src:blancmange/asida] 1465–1550), the Arab explorer known as Hasan al-Wazan in the Arab world.
[src:blancmange/asida] According to the French scholar Maxime Rodinson, asida were typical foods among the Bedouin of pre-Islamic and, probably, later times.
[src:blancmange/asida] In the old city of Fez, vendors sell squares of cold semolina pudding sprinkled with sugar and cinnamon, usually consumed by children after school.
[src:blancmange/asida] The Libyan variation of asida is served with a sweet syrup, usually date or carob syrup (rub), but also with honey, as well as melted butter around the asida itself.
[src:blancmange/asida] Asida (Aseeda) is made primarily as a dessert by Palestinians.
[src:blancmange/asida] It serves as a both a comfort food and a dish to mark special occasions.
[src:blancmange/asida] The dessert version is served with honey or date syrup, and for special occasions might see the addition of sauteed nuts and cinnamon.
[src:blancmange/asida] A savory dish also called asida but consisting of stewed wheat berries with lamb is made in at least one village in Palestine at times of mourning, attesting to the uniqueness and specificity of local food customs.
[src:blancmange/asida] The Tunisian version of this dish is served with either a mixture of honey and butter or a hot chili pepper paste (harissa).
[src:blancmange/asida] The latter is more common later in the day and the former earlier.
[src:blancmange/asida] Asida is also commonly consumed with carob syrup or date syrup in southern parts of Tunisia.
[src:blancmange/asida] Aseedah or aseed (Arabic: عصيدة) is one of the staple dishes in Yemen and is usually served for lunch, dinner, or breakfast.
[src:blancmange/asida] Its ingredients include wholemeal wheat, boiling water, and salt as needed.
[src:blancmange/asida] A pot of water is placed on high heat until boiling.
[src:blancmange/asida] Slowly, handfuls of wholemeal wheat are added and then mixed quickly with a large wooden spoon to avoid forming lumps.
[src:blancmange/asida] The process is repeated until the mixture is thick.
[src:blancmange/asida] Traditionally the cook lowers the pot to the floor where they hold the pot with their feet and stir vigorously.
[src:blancmange/asida] Finally, the hot, steaming dough is shaped using bare oiled hands and usually placed in a wide, wooden bowl.
[src:blancmange/asida] Sometimes a depression is made in the middle of the shaped aseedah into which a hot chili tomato paste can be added or helba, a fenugreek mixture made with parsley and garlic.
[src:blancmange/asida] Lamb or a chicken stock is then poured around the aseedah.
[src:blancmange/asida] Aseedah can also be made using white, bleached wheat.
[src:blancmange/asida] Honey can be used instead of stock and chili/helba.
[src:blancmange/asida] It is a meal, using only boiled water, flour, and some salt.
[src:blancmange/asida] Typically it is smothered in beef soup or chicken or even lamb.
[src:blancmange/asida] It is usually served hot and eaten with hands or spoons.
[src:blancmange/asida] Aseed is eaten particularly at lunchtime and during Ramadan.
[src:blancmange/asida] The Ethiopian version of this dish is called genfo in Amharic.
[src:blancmange/asida] It is served with Ethiopian ghee (called niter kibbeh), berbere (an Ethiopian spice mix), yogurt, or even milk.
[src:blancmange/asida] It is popular during Ramadan, and is often served with a meat-and-tomato sauce.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] It is usually set in a mould and served cold.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Although traditionally white, blancmanges are frequently given other colours.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Blancmange originated at some time during the Middle Ages from the older Middle Eastern *muhallebi*, and usually consisted of capon or chicken, milk or almond milk, rice, and sugar; it was considered to be an ideal food for the sick.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Similar desserts include Bavarian cream, Italian *panna cotta*, Turkish *tavuk göğsü*, Brazilian *manjar branco*, Chinese almond tofu, Hawai'ian *haupia* and Puerto Rican *tembleque*.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The origins of the blancmange have long been believed to lie in the introduction of rice and almonds in early medieval Europe by Arab traders.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Recently, it has been shown that there have been similar Arab dishes from that period such as muhallebi.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Muhallebi, or another similar dish from the medieval Islamic world, spread to Europe first as *blanc-manger* in France, later translated to *biancomangiare* in Italy and *manjar blanco* in Spain.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The oldest recipe for blancmange is from the oldest extant Danish cookbook, written by Henrik Harpestræng, who died in 1244, which dates it to the early 13th century at the latest.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The work may be a translation of a German cookbook, which is believed to have been based on a Latin or Romance vernacular manuscript from the 12th century or even earlier.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The "whitedish" (from the original Old French term *blanc manger*) was a dish consumed by the upper-classes and common to most of Europe during the Middle Ages and early modern period.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] It occurs in countless variations from recipe collections from all over Europe and was one of the few truly international dishes of medieval and early modern Europe.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] It is mentioned in the prologue to Geoffrey Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales* and in an early 15th-century cookbook written by the chefs of Richard II.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The basic ingredients were milk or almond milk, sugar, and shredded chicken (usually capon) or fish, often combined with rosewater and rice flour, and mixed into a bland stew.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Almond milk and fish were used as substitutes for the other animal products on fast days and Lent.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] It was also often flavoured with spices such as saffron or cinnamon and the chicken could be exchanged for other fowl, such as quail or partridge.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Spices were often used in recipes of the later Middle Ages since they were considered prestigious.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] On festive occasions and among the upper classes, whitedishes were often rendered more festive by colouring agents: the reddish-golden yellow of saffron; green with various herbs; or sandalwood for russet.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] In 14th-century France, parti-colouring (the use of two bright contrasting colours on the same plate) was especially popular and was described by Guillaume Tirel (also known as *Taillevent*), one of the primary authors of the later editions of *Le Viandier*.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The brightly coloured whitedishes were one of the most common of the early entremets: edibles that were intended to entertain and delight through a gaudy appearance as much as through flavour.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] In the 17th century, the whitedish evolved into a meatless dessert pudding with cream and eggs, and later, gelatin.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] In the 19th century, arrowroot and cornflour were added, and the dish evolved into the modern blancmange.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The word blancmange derives from Old French *blanc mangier*.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] The name "whitedish" is a modern term used by some historians, though the name historically was either a direct translation from or a calque of the Old French term.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Though it is fairly certain that the etymology is indeed "white dish", medieval sources are not always consistent as to the actual colour of the dish.
[src:blancmange/blancmange] Food scholar Terence Scully has proposed the alternative etymology of *bland mangier*, "bland dish", reflecting its often mild and "dainty" (in this context meaning refined and aristocratic) taste and popularity as a dish for the sick.
